06007nam a22011295i 9780691209807DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020033754  a97806912098077 a10.1515/97806912098072doi  a(DE-B1597)566231  a(OCoLC)1182021838  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aBM496.9.T47 4aBM496.9.T47bK38 2021 7aREL0400902bisacsh04a296.12231 aKattan Gribetz, Sarit, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTime and Difference in Rabbinic Judaism /cSarit Kattan Gribetz. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b11 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Rabbinic and Roman Time -- tChapter 2. Jewish and Christian Time -- tChapter 3. Men’s and Women’s Time -- tChapter 4. Human and Divine Time -- tConclusion: Temporal Legacies: What Difference Does Time Make -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tFigure Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow the rabbis of late antiquity used time to define the boundaries of Jewish identityThe rabbinic corpus begins with a question—"when?"—and is brimming with discussions about time and the relationship between people, God, and the hour. Time and Difference in Rabbinic Judaism explores the rhythms of time that animated the rabbinic world of late antiquity, revealing how rabbis conceptualized time as a way of constructing difference between themselves and imperial Rome, Jews and Christians, men and women, and human and divine.In each chapter, Sarit Kattan Gribetz explores a unique aspect of rabbinic discourse on time. She shows how the ancient rabbinic texts artfully subvert Roman imperialism by offering "rabbinic time" as an alternative to "Roman time." She examines rabbinic discourse about the Sabbath, demonstrating how the weekly day of rest marked "Jewish time" from "Christian time." Gribetz looks at gendered daily rituals, showing how rabbis created "men's time" and "women's time" by mandating certain rituals for men and others for women. She delves into rabbinic writings that reflect on how God spends time and how God's use of time relates to human beings, merging "divine time" with "human time." Finally, she traces the legacies of rabbinic constructions of time in the medieval and modern periods.Time and Difference in Rabbinic Judaism sheds new light on the central role that time played in the construction of Jewish identity, subjectivity, and theology during this transformative period in the history of Judaism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aRabbinical literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aTime in rabbinical literature. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Theology.2bisacsh  aBible.  aChristian calendar.  aChristian theology.  aChristianity.  aElisheva Carlebach.  aGod.  aJesus.  aJewish calendar.  aJewish theology.  aLynn Kaye.  aPalaces of Time.  aRoman Empire.  aRoman calendar.  aSacha Stern.  aSunday.  aTalmud.  aTemporality.  aTime and Process in Ancient Judaism.  aTime in the Babylonian Talmud.  abiblical studies.  acalendar.  agender.  ahistory of Christianity.  apolemic.  apurity.  arabbinics.  ashema.  atemple.  atheology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACK